In the center of the trench set between the east and the west walls.

Phase IV: Nabataean Grand Design: 1st c. BCE to CE 1st c. The tetrastyle in antis temple is built, including the Porch extension, stylobate, Porch columns, East, West and South Corridor walls, East and West Walkway Walls and the East and West Porch Antae. Additionally, the limestone flooring from Phase II is extended at this time to cover the surfaces of the new corridors and walkways.

Part I) This is the neatly fitted pavement of the West Walkway consisting of 20 extant limestone pavers plus fragments of others. They are set in irregular courses of headers and stretchers. The pavement has been damaged by collapse and some pavers are robbed out in the south end of the Part I trench. In Part II, only three pavers survived in the southeast corner of the trench. In Part III there are 10 such pavers extant. The largest stretchers measure 1.10 m in length-by-0.55 m in width. When the pavers are present they lie approximately 0.07 m above the elevation of the West Corridor floor.
Bottom elevation: 2.25 m below Point A, Part I or 886.05 m. 3.67 m below Point E, Part III or 885.94 m.

The floor pavers measure 6.20 north south-by-3.30 m in width at their widest point in the north. They range in width from ca. 0.05 to ca. 0.07 m. In the south end of Part I they cover only 1.60 m in area. They have been robbed out for most of the Part II and Part III areas, but in Part III some 10 pavers were still found in situ.
Installation of the West Corridor floor pavement.
Locus 1 debris, Part I; Locus 7 debris, Part II; and Locus 10 debris, Part III.
Top elevation: 2.18 m below Point A, Part I or 886.05 m. 3.60 m below Point E, Part III or 886.01 m.
